## Learned Workspace Facts

- Cloudflare R2 publications: single bucket (`TAU_S3_BUCKET` env-driven) + namespace prefixes hard-coded as constants in `libs/types` (not env vars — prefixes are architecture, not config); CDN via `cloudflare_r2_custom_domain` + zone cache rules (no Worker hot path); MinIO local parity.
- UI deployment topology (staging Netlify site `taucad`, production `taucad-prod-us`, Fly-hosted APIs) is spelled out in `docs/architecture/ui-deployment-topology.md`. Production-US Netlify dashboard env vars (NODE*ENV, TAU_API_URL, TAU_WEBSOCKET_URL, TAU_FRONTEND_URL) are managed by Terraform via `repos/cloud-infra/modules/netlify-site` `plain_environment_variables` (functions+runtime scope; toml + tfvars must be reviewed together — HCP plan diff catches drift). `prod-us` suffix on stack/site/HCP-workspace names anticipates additional regional production sites (`prod-eu`, etc.). Companion Terraform manifests for `repos/cloud-infra` are cloned via `pnpm repos sync`; operator docs entry at `repos/cloud-infra/docs/`. Cloud-infra IaC layout: HashiCorp Terraform (NOT OpenTofu — verdict accepted because HCP Terraform Cloud's managed secrets/state outweigh the BSL license cost), Stacks-based deployment topology with one stack per environment under `repos/cloud-infra/stacks/cloud/{staging,prod-us}/` (each stack has its own `terraform.auto.tfvars` and HCP workspace), shared modules under `repos/cloud-infra/modules/{cloudflare-dns,netlify-site}/`, `tfenv` 1.14.5 pinned via `.terraform-version` (auto-installs via `TFENV_AUTO_INSTALL=true`), `.tflint.hcl` for static checks, CI at `.github/workflows/terraform.yml`. Cloudflare is the DNS authority across the board (migrated off Namecheap for both `taucad.dev` staging and `tau.new` prod) — DNS records authored via the `cloudflare-dns` module; never use `is_prod` boolean discriminators (designed from the start for `staging`/`prod-us`/future `prod-eu`); `~/.netrc` files with non-keyword content (e.g. a `baseUrl` line) break Terraform provider downloads with `Error parsing netrc file ... line 1: keyword expected; got baseUrl` — clean or remove the file before `terraform init`; the `repos/cloud-infra/modules/netlify-site` `netlify_site_build_settings` resource MUST explicitly set `base_directory` (e.g. `apps/ui`) for both staging git-mode and prod-us CI-mode stacks — omitting it sends `null` to the Netlify provider which silently wipes any previously-set dashboard `base`, after which Netlify scans the repo root for `netlify.toml`, finds none, logs `No config file was defined`, emits zero SSR functions / zero header rules, and 404s every route (smoking gun: deploy summary shows `0 functions deployed` despite a successful build); once `base_directory = "apps/ui"` is set, every path inside `apps/ui/netlify.toml` becomes base-relative — `publish` MUST be `"build/client"` (NOT `"apps/ui/build/client"`, which path-doubles to `apps/ui/apps/ui/build/client`); CI-mode silently strips `base_directory` from API responses but it should still be declared for intent and to future-proof switching back to git-mode. `apps/ui/netlify.toml` is the source of truth for non-sensitive env vars (Netlify dashboard env vars intentionally kept empty so the toml is authoritative; only sensitive secrets stay in dashboard); GitHub Actions package.json field extraction must use `pnpm pkg get <field>` (not brittle `awk`/`sed`) so version/script reads stay consistent across CI scripts; `apps/ui/app/routes.ts` is intentionally minimal — prefer file-based routing under `apps/ui/app/routes/` (e.g. `assets.$/route.tsx` for splat catch-alls) over manual `routes.ts` declarations; `netlify.toml` env vars are build-time only — not available in SSR functions, so derive runtime values in `environment.config.ts` preprocess; `NX_PREFER_NODE_STRIP_TYPES=true` must be inlined in build commands (Nx evaluates at module load, before `.env` files); `apps/ui` requires `tslib` as a runtime dependency (not devDep) because `react-router-serve` runs the built bundle in production (Fly.io UI image start failure mode); per-project `build.outputs` overrides in `project.json` that point to non-existent paths silently break NX cache restore (manifests as `size-limit` "can't find files" failures) — rely on the inherited `outputs: ["{projectRoot}/dist"]` from `tools/tsdown.plugin.ts` rather than hand-rolled overrides; PostHog analytics loaded lazily via `posthog.lib.ts` — static import blocks main thread ~2.5s during startup; Shiki syntax highlighting grammars loaded on-demand (not eagerly imported); `@taucad/converter` exports separate entry points: `@taucad/converter/formats` provides lightweight format metadata (extensions, MIME types) without importing full conversion/import/export dependencies; `mimeTypes` in `mime-types.constants.ts` is the single source of truth for 3D file extensions — `fileExtensions`/`fileExtensionSet`/`createExportFile` derived from it; `ExportFormat` type removed — use `FileExtension`; converter `importFormatKeys` derived from `fileExtensions` with `unsupportedImports` exclusion set; `packages/converter` `import.test.ts` baselines round-trip assertions on `standardCubeGeometry` via `createCubeTestCase('<fmt>', { variant, geometry: standardCubeGeometry })` — per-format deviations from the gold-standard shape indicate incomplete assimp normalization (importer/exporter transform gap or fixture mismatch) rather than legitimate format differences and warrant investigation; cross-origin isolation uses `COEP: require-corp` (not `credentialless`) for universal browser support including Safari — all external resources are same-origin proxied (PostHog via `/api/ph`, GitHub avatars via `/api/github-avatar`), so `require-corp` works without breakage; `apps/ui/server.ts` is a custom Express server (replacing `react-router-serve`) that wires `coiMiddleware` from `@taucad/runtime/cross-origin-isolation/express` so localhost dev/SSR ships the COOP/COEP headers Safari needs to enable `SharedArrayBuffer` (the same middleware is exported as a public runtime entry point so 3rd-party Express consumers can adopt it without re-implementing the headers); the consumer-facing setup is documented at `apps/ui/content/docs/(runtime)/guides/cross-origin-isolation.mdx`. `nx serve ui` (the built production server, not `nx dev ui`) supports `--host` (LAN binding, derived from `tools/runtime-lan-ips.mjs`) and `--https` (mkcert-backed dev CA + COOP/COEP so iOS Safari and other LAN devices can reach `SharedArrayBuffer`) — `nx dev ui` MUST NOT prompt for sudo (no implicit mkcert install in dev), HTTPS is opt-in only via the `--https` flag on `serve`; certificate plumbing is centralised under `apps/ui/app/lib/certificates/` (cert paths, mkcert wiring, server-args parsing) with a `vite-plugin-mkcert` patch to suppress sudo prompts; when `--https --host` are both set, the boot banner renders an ASCII QR pair (CA-install QR + page-link QR with explicit "Trust the dev CA" / "Open in browser" labels) above the Local/Network URL list, and the rationale copy explains \_why* (Tau ships SharedArrayBuffer-backed CAD transports → cross-origin isolation → HTTPS on every non-loopback origin including Safari) so devs aren't left wondering why a QR appeared. Production deploys follow a **GitOps trail-PR** flow modelled on `novuhq/novu`: a continuously-rebased `main → production` PR is force-pushed by CI on every merge to `main`, has zero required PR checks (humans verify staging post-merge before approving), and merging it triggers Netlify Git-integration prod deploys plus Fly API deploys via `push` workflows — the legacy "manual deploy" workflow was removed. GitHub repo settings (rulesets for `main` and `production` branches, GitHub environments, teams, ruleset bypass actors) live in their own Terraform stack under `repos/cloud-infra/stacks/repo` using the `integrations/github` provider (HCP workspace `tau-repo`) — replaces hand-curated branch protection. The default GitHub Actions `GITHUB_TOKEN` CANNOT create PRs (`createPullRequest` GraphQL returns "GitHub Actions is not permitted to create or approve pull requests") so the trail-PR workflow runs under a dedicated **GitHub App release bot** (separate from the IaC bot) with a generated private key, granted `pull_requests:write` + `contents:write`, and listed in the production ruleset's bypass actors. Nx Cloud cache tokens are split into **read-write and read-only**: `NX_CLOUD_ACCESS_TOKEN_READ_WRITE` is scoped to the `main` GitHub environment only so only main-branch pushes write the Nx cache (prevents PR-build cache poisoning), and the `production` environment receives `NX_CLOUD_ACCESS_TOKEN_READ_ONLY` so prod release CI reads cached builds without writing — use the full `_READ_WRITE`/`_READ_ONLY` suffixes (no `_RW`/`_RO` abbreviations) for readability. GitHub environments split into **`main` / `staging` / `production`** (the prior `review-ui` environment was retired when prod-UI moved to Netlify-only); Fly deploy tokens are **per-app** (not per-org) and live in the matching environment so a compromised staging token cannot reach prod. Netlify secret env vars created via `netlify_environment_variable { is_secret = true }` MUST list explicit `contexts` — the API rejects `'all'` with **`422 Unprocessable Entity: "Secrets are not allowed to have 'All contexts' context. Explicitly set which contexts to use."`** so the `netlify-site` module enumerates `['production', 'deploy-preview', 'branch-deploy']` per secret. Production UI CI runs `netlify build` (Netlify CLI) instead of the prior bespoke `nx build ui` + manual `netlify deploy` chain so staging and prod produce byte-identical SSR function bundles.
